But, online channel is very small and not too relevant for us. We can ignore that in the short term. People tend to do their reservations from the stores.Accurately measuring lost sales could be difficult because based on Daves comment people tend to replace their missing pieces when the items they reserved are not available.Reservation related tables are snapshot and gets updated live. For us they are the same thing

s not familiar with it.DC & HUB terms are being used interchangeably. For us they are the same thing. The inventory is kept at the DC but goes through the HUB  during the rental process.For the wedding events negative inventory values could show up in the reservation screen however, in the non-wedding events they would not show up.Their busiest season is on May. Because approximately 50% of the business is prom and 50% is wedding. Thats the most difficult time of the year for themProm is much more complex then wedding, mainly because:For wedding events  the # of days between reservation commit and event is ~ 70 daysFor prom event  the # of days between reservation commit and event is 9 daysBy default, pickup date is 2 days before the event, for grooms its 4 days. Return date is 1 day after the event. These dates can change during reservation. i.e. if the event is in a cruz, then it will not return next day

ates can change during reservation. i.e. if the event is in a cruz, then it will not return next day. they call it extended rentalCustomers  can extend the return date by paying extraHub to hub avg transfer lead time is 3 days.The items in a reservation is blocked during the period of approximately 10 days before the event and 3 days after the event. My understanding is that the TUX_BOOKINGS table is being used to calculate that.Term production refers to the assembly(pickup) of the items within the package at the DC

culate that.Term production refers to the assembly(pickup) of the items within the package at the DC. - In June, after seeing April & May rental reservation demand, next years forecasts & season buy is determined. There is nothing much to do for the same years Fall Season in terms of purchasing new inventory, because its too close. Total buy projections for the next year is provided to the vendor. After the projections are sent, in a couple of weeks the purchase orders are created.
- July & August period is when DC rebalance activities intensifies. Because they start to see the reservations for the peak demand (Sept-Oct), they try to reallocate available inventory among the DCs.

- In November, next years season buy plan is revisited. They also update next years Fall season forecasts because they have more recent peak demand data (recently actualized Sept-Oct). Similar to the exercise in June, they provide additional projections to vendors and then convert them into purchase orders in a couple of weeks. Depending on the forecasts etc. they might cancel the purchase orders created in June -if possible- as well.
- Feb & March is pretty much same as July & August. Before the Spring Peak, after seeing some of the reservations, they try to rebalance the DC inventory levels based on the available inventory + purchase orders that are going to be received before March 15th.
